<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-525-744  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 525 744.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>ACM Transactions on Programming Languages andamp; Systems  April 1990v12 n2 p178(25).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Linguistic support for atomic data types. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weihl, William E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many applications, such as banking systems, airline reservationsystems, and office automation systems, find the manipulation andpreservation of long-lived, online data to be of primaryimportance.andP;  These systems must preserve the consistency of theironline data in the presence of concurrency and hardware failures.andO;Transactions that use and manipulate atomic data are helpful insupporting consistency.andP;  Two properties of atomic transactions areserializability, the concurrent execution of a group oftransactions is equivalent to some serial execution of the sametransactions; and recoverability, each transaction appears to beall-or-nothing.andP;  An approach in which atomicity is accomplishedthrough the shared data objects, which must be implemented so thatthe transactions using them appear to be atomic, avoids most ofthe problems of existing proposals.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Program Development TechniquesDistributed SystemsConcurrency ControlOn-Line Transaction ProcessingAbstract Data Types.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Informal specification of the data type semiqueue. (chart)Implicit implementation of the data type semiqueue. (chart)Informal specification of the data type aid. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>